deck: Younger son of Kaguya Ōtsutsuki and brother to the Sage of the Six Paths, with whom he fought and sealed the Ten-Tails. He wielded the Byakugan and went on to become the ancestor of the Hyūga clan, as well as the founder of the Shinobi of the Moon.
description:
Origin

Hamura Ōtsutsuki was born along with his brother, Hagoromo, to Kaguya Ōtsutsuki, an alien princess who came to Earth in pursuit of the Divine Tree, a thousand years before the main story began. As such, they were the first two humans born with the ability to wield chakra.

In the anime, it was revealed that Tenji, the Emperor of the Land of Ancestors (祖の国, So no Kuni), was their father.

Years later, Hamura and Hagoromo had grown up and, along with their mother, became the rulers of the Land in which they lived.

At one point in time, however, Kaguya began to grow angry that her sons inherited the chakra that she felt was solely hers. So, unbeknownst to Hamura and his brother, she fused with the Divine Tree and became the Ten-Tailed beast, in an effort to reclaim the chakra that was passed down to her sons at birth.

Hagoromo and Hamura successfully defeated the beast and then sealed it inside Hagoromo, making him the first Jinchūriki. Hamura then went to the moon that Hagoromo created and sealed the husk of the Ten-Tails in, and lived there to stand guard over it until his death, but not before bearing a child that would become the progenitor of the Hyūga clan.

A thousand years later, one of his descendants, Toneri, saw that the world that Hagoromo created was a failure, and so he chose to destroy it by dropping the Moon on the Earth. This went against Hamura's wishes, and when his spirit encountered Hinata, he then gave her the task of destroying the Tenseigan and preventing the world's destruction.

Powers

His full abilities have not yet been expanded upon, but it is known that he was a very powerful individual, being one of the first to be born with chakra, and being the one who assisted his brother in defeating the Ten-Tailed Beast.

He was also a wielder of the Byakugan, with which he was skilled in its use and would pass down to his descendants, the Hyūga.

deck: Violent Veteran From The Zone and Leader of Gangreen
description:
Origin

Suicida was amongst the many US Soldiers who were experimented on before being sent out into "The Zone", a future war that took place in South America, he served beside Marshal Law.

These people were altered to make them into Super Soldiers, they were given a range of different super powers, as well as having their ability to feel pain and empathy dampened.

On returning after the war Suicida, like many of the soldiers who fought in The Zone suffered from post-traumatic stress disorder, having difficulty controlling his aggression and being prone to extreme violent outbursts he found it impossible to readjust and return to normal life. Suicida ended up forming a malicious gang of unwanted, crazy Zone veterans, which he named "Gangreen"

Unlike the majority of Zone veterans, Suicida shares Marshal Law's deep-seated hatred for Public Spirit.

Creation

Suicida was created by Pat Mills and Kevin O'Neil and appeared in the first issue of their Marshal Law Miniseries published by Epic Comics, an imprint of Marvel.

Being that the series was creator owned, Suicida moved from publisher to publisher.

Powers

Like all veterans of "The Zone" Suicida has had something that is known as a Pain-Gate surgically implanted into his body, this limits the amount of pain he is able to feel to easily bearable levels.

He also has some level of super-strength and durability, able to survive falls from lethal heights, as well as fight and keep up with the likes of Marshal Law and Savage Dragon.
name: Suicida

description:
Origin

Buck Caine was one of the earliest experiments by Doctor Shocc at creating a super human, his mother had agreed to allow genetic manipulation of her unborn fetus whilst it was in the womb.

The experiments were a resounding success, giving Buck a variety of different superpowers and abilities, he was unveiled to the general public and held up as role model for everyone to aspire to.

After some time he was sent off to explore space, during his time away war broke out and his story and fame was used to inspire young soldiers to undergo their own genetic enhancements.

Creation

The Public Spirit was created by Pat Mills and Kevin O'Neil for their creator owned comic, Marshal Law, which was initially published by Marvel's adult imprint Epic Comics.

Major Story Arcs

Fear and Loathing

After returning from his trips in outer space The Public Spirit came home to much fanfare, but a select few felt that he had been reckless and irresponsible as a role model, glorifying blind patriotism, war and genetic manipulation to the extent that he should be held partially responsible for all the soldiers who had died during the course of the war, as well as those driven crazy by the experiments done to them.

It was also discovered that The Public Spirit did in fact also have some skeleton's in his closet, underneath his jovial exterior as a crusader of justice he was, in fact, a selfish, self absorbed, and dangerous man, a man who had years previously attempted to murder his pregnant girlfriend due to the belief that the birth of a love-child could negatively affect his career.

His ex-girlfriend and their son eventually came back for revenge, this time The Public Spirit made sure he would not make the same mistake twice, and beat her to death with his bare hands.

Martial Law eventually caught up with him, and after a long fight the Public Spirit was executed by a government sniper, the higher ups had come to the conclusion that he had become a liability.

Powers

The Public Spirit is an analogue of Superman, and as such has a similar repertoire of abilities
name: The Public Spirit

deck: Pinkie Pie's older sister who has a deep knowledge and fascination with rocks.
description:
Maud is Pinkie's older sister, who is very knowledgeable about geology. She grew up on the rock farm and is getting her "rocktorate" (like doctorate) in Rock Science. While she has a deadpan voice and sense of humor, she is not without emotions. She cares for Pinkie Pie, demonstrating this by rescuing her from a rock slide and hugging her when she was safe. She also has kept all the rock candy necklaces that Pinkie has traded her over the years, stating that she doesn't really like candy, but she does love Pinkie Pie. She also gave back the rock pouch that Pinkie gave her, after finding out she had paid for it by giving away her party canon. After getting the canon back (in exchange for the pouch), she explained to Pinkie that gift-giving isn't a competition of who can give better presents; it's an expression of love.

She has a pet rock named Boulder.

She always wears a blue frock, which obscures her Cutie Mark, which is a diamond. She likes to write both verse and free-verse poetry about rocks.

deck: A Pirate who comes into contact with Crazy Dave and friends in the Plants vs. Zombies universe.
description:
Major Story Arcs

Timepocalypse

Chestbeard has a giant beard on his chest, out of which various disgusting sea creatures occasionally poke. He runs a pirate crew, including Cracker-Jackie, Hawg Dawg, Philip the Dark, Doubloon Drawers, Bubblepipe Pirate, and Otis the Oarsman, and has buried a chest of treasure on Eye Island. Unbeknownst to him, among the pieces of treasure is a piece of Zomboss's sun vacuum.

Both Patrice and Nate, and Zomboss, try to get the sun vacuum part out of the chest. However, Chestbeard also wants to dig his treasure up.

Patrice manages to distract Chestbeard with some balloons, and gets away with the sun vacuum piece.

Chestbeard somehow gets lost in time and ends up as a pizza delivery man. He delivers some pizza to Patrice, Dave, and Nate, and they all become friends.

Chestbeard's Revenge

A backup story in Grown Sweet Home relates how Chestbeard time travels to Neighborville to conquer it, but has his chest shaved by Crazy Dave's Robot Orange Juice. Shamed, Chestbeard retreats.

Petal to the Metal

Chestbeard shows up in Nate's dream, and tells him the best way to win a race is to board the other ships. Upon waking, Nate and Patrice take Chestbeard's advice and attack the Zombies' cars. The strategy is effective: the Zombies' cars are destroyed and the Zombies are abandoned in the desert.

Boom Boom Mushroom

Chestbeard uses a "legendary" huge, greasy rubber band to keep his chest beard in a ponytail. It is later hidden underground in the caves beneath Neighborville, only to be found by Twister. Nate and Patrice use it to cross a river in their quest to defeat Zomboss's plans.

deck: An alien girl chosen by Kyle Rayner to receive the power of the Life Equation before his departure into the Source.
description:
Creation

Saysoran was created by Justin Jordan and Diogenes Neves in Green Lantern: New Guardians: Futures End #1.

Futures End

Five years in the future of the DCU, Kyle Rayner has mastered the power of the Life Equation and become more than just the White Lantern ---- he has become a being who can change men, worlds and the universe through sheer force of will, and burdened with the knowledge of a dark and predatory cosmos, resolves to use his power to bring peace to all life. Over the years, he accomplishes this by visiting countless planets and altering the minds of all the inhabitants, driving away violence and anger from their minds, and leaving them only with the desire to live in happiness with their fellows.

On one such world, he fails to convert everyone, as a young girl named Saysoran resists every attempt to turn her mind and escapes from her family and friends, who all try to show her what they have been shown by the Life Equation. She boards a spacecraft for Kyle's cosmic abode, deep in space, and upon arrival hears Kyle's voice in her ear, telling her that he has arranged for her to find him. Kyle tells her that though his power is infinite and his knowledge unlimited, he is plagued by doubt, and that Saysoran possesses the one thing he does not: the perspective to judge his actions from outside.

When he manifests before her eyes, Saysoran calls him insane, and attacks him with weapons from the abode. Unharmed, Kyle admits that she may be right about him, and muses that the possibility of his insanity is part of the problem. He marvels at the fact that of all the billions upon billions of minds that he has turned, each possessing the ability to resist him, only she succeeded in doing so, and asks her why she would resist him if she saw the pain and suffering that exists throughout the universe. Saysoran angrily counters that she resists because Kyle has no right to decide the fates of others, and that everyone has to find their own version of happiness their own way.

Kyle reveals that his life is nearly over, as he will soon merge with the Source itself, and needs someone worthy to take the power of the Life Equation from him and carry on. He tells Saysoran that all of what she has experienced has been a test, to judge her suitability, and that he has found her worthy of the task. In a flash of light, he fades away, leaving only the white ring behind. His voice tells Saysoran that only she can judge him; that she can undo all he has wrought, or she can carry on from where he left off. He tells her that he cannot force her to accept the responsibility, and that only she can decide. As his voice fades, Saysoran slips the ring onto her finger, and ascends to become the universe's new White Lantern.
